title: Do We Earn Our Salvation? Grace, Works & the Catholic View Explained
description:
Do Catholics believe we earn our salvation? It's one of the most misunderstood—and most debated—questions in all of Christianity. And today, we're setting the record straight with clarity, Scripture, and a whole lot of grace.

In this video, we dig deep into what the Catholic Church actually teaches about faith, grace, and works. Spoiler alert: it’s not salvation by works. But it’s also not a passive, one-time decision that guarantees heaven regardless of how we live.

We’ll walk through:

What St. Paul really meant by “justified by faith apart from works of the law” (Romans 3:28).

Why James says we’re “justified by works and not by faith alone” (James 2:24)—and why Martin Luther tried to downplay this book.

How grace is always the initiator and sustainer of salvation—yet that grace empowers us to respond with faith working through love (Galatians 5:6).

What the Council of Trent clarified in response to the Reformation—and why its teachings are deeply rooted in Scripture and tradition.

How salvation is best understood as a relationship, not a legal transaction—something we must remain faithful in, like a marriage, not just a moment we mentally check off.

We'll also break down the false dichotomy between faith and works, and show how the Catholic view doesn’t contradict Scripture—it completes the picture.

So if you’ve ever wondered whether Catholics “do” too much or Protestants “assume” too much when it comes to salvation, this is the video for you. Let’s talk about what it means to be saved by grace through faith, and what role our response actually plays in the process.

Come with humility, come with questions, and most of all—come with an open heart. Because salvation isn’t about ticking boxes. It’s about becoming who you were made to be, by grace.

title: The Early Church Fathers on Apostolic Succession: Part 2 of the Unbroken Chain
description:
How do we know the Catholic Church today teaches the same faith the Apostles handed down? In Part 2 of our series on apostolic succession, we turn to the powerhouse voices of the early Church—those who lived closest to the time of Christ and the Apostles—to see what they actually believed and taught.

This episode focuses on what the Church Fathers said about apostolic succession, and spoiler alert: it wasn’t just a nice tradition. It was essential for identifying the true Church. St. Irenaeus, writing in the second century, lays it out clearly: if you want to know which church has the true teaching, you look for the one that can trace its bishops back to the Apostles. Plain and simple.

We’ll examine quotes and context from:

St. Ignatius of Antioch (writing as early as 107 AD),

St. Irenaeus of Lyons, who dismantled heresies by pointing to apostolic lineage,

Tertullian, who argued that heretics had no right to interpret Scripture because they weren’t in the apostolic chain.

This isn’t just history—it’s a defense of doctrinal authority and unity that the Church has preserved for 2,000 years. And if you’re coming from a Protestant background, this may be a missing piece that helps explain how the early Church stayed grounded without splintering every time someone had a new interpretation of the Bible.

So, if you’re ready to hear how the earliest Christians understood authority, succession, and Church unity—grab your notebook, buckle in, and let the Fathers speak for themselves. Their words still echo with clarity, conviction, and continuity.

So grab your Bible, maybe a highlighter, and let’s go back to the very first bishops—because to understand the Church today, you’ve got to understand where it came from.

title: Does The Soul Exist? The Truth Science Can’t Explain
description:
What makes you… you? Is your identity just a product of brain chemistry and biological processes, or is there something deeper—something immaterial that gives you true self-awareness, free will, and purpose?

In this episode of Practical Theism, we tackle one of the most profound questions of human existence: Do we have souls?

Modern science can explain how our bodies function, but it struggles to define what life actually is—or why we possess the ability to reason, reflect, and long for meaning beyond mere survival. If we were nothing more than biological machines, our thoughts and choices would be nothing but chemical reactions. And yet, we experience love, morality, and the ability to defy our instincts. Why?

Drawing from philosophy, Scripture, and theology, we explore:

Why the soul isn’t just a metaphor, but the very thing that animates us
How personal identity persists, even though every physical part of us regenerates over time
The mysterious nature of consciousness, and why near-death experiences challenge a purely materialistic view of life
Why free will, rational thought, and moral reasoning point to something beyond the physical
The teachings of St. Thomas Aquinas, C.S. Lewis, and the Catechism on the soul’s immortality
If we have a soul, then our existence doesn’t end with death—and everything we do carries eternal weight.

This is more than just a philosophical debate. It’s a question that shapes how we live, what we value, and what we believe about our ultimate destiny.

So, what do you think? Is the soul real, or are we just neurons firing in a random universe? Let’s discuss in the comments.

title: What Is Ash Wednesday?
description:
Ash Wednesday—what's the deal with all the ashes? Are Catholics just walking around with dirt on their foreheads for tradition’s sake, or is there something deeper happening here?

In this episode of Practical Theism, we break down the biblical, historical, and spiritual significance of Ash Wednesday. From Genesis to the early Church, we explore why ashes symbolize repentance, mortality, and our need for God’s mercy. Plus, we tackle common misconceptions—like whether Jesus condemned public displays of faith—and why even Protestant reformers kept this tradition alive.

Lent is about prayer, fasting, and almsgiving—but it’s more than just giving things up. It’s about becoming more like Christ. So don’t just wear the ashes. Live them.
